 them props?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Perhaps because I've seen my fiance assembly-lined through doctor offices, tagged with something he didn't have after the doctor had asked about 5 questions total, cursorily given a prescription that may or may not have made him worse, and sent away until the next appointment, where much the same process was repeated.  Or maybe because he's been to 5 or so clinics and at every one they tossed aside his previous records and re-did all of the expensive scans and tests he had had done 2-3 times before.  Or because, once most of them had decided (however callously) what they thought he had, they would listen to none of his arguments and evidence against it, nor the fact that the medicine was not helping (and sometimes making him worse), for as much as a year and a half (the longest he stayed with such a doctor).<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Trust me, doctors feel like SHIT when they miss something or do something that hurts a patient<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Maybe you do, and certainly 2-3 of the doctors we have encountered did, but the vast majority did not seem to.  Several blamed nascens when the treatment did not work, saying that if he really wanted to get better he would, or if he were really following their instructions he would be well.  Almost all of them had the familiar &quot;God Complex,&quot; so sure that they were right that they would yell at nascens if he questioned them.  One put him on a very dangerous combination of medication that messed him up severely, and caused serious side effects.. then the doctor yelled at nascens for &quot;obviously not doing something right,&quot; sending him even further down the spiral.  We trusted him, he was very high up and prestigious, so stayed with him for a year and a half...but that did it.<br><br>Anyhow.  Thank goodness for the research tools available today, and that we figured out what he had, or I'm not sure what would've happened.<br><br>Disclaimer: all the doctors above were encountered in the South, and we all know how advance the technology and science is down there...<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Removed some personal information at the request of the poster and person involved. The information does not change the point of the post at all, and had no bearing on the discussion. It was merely personal medical information that was removed. -Tarot</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/utarotoflanys.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TarotofLanys</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://dr.drakeramoray.50megs.com/10x10/3leafclover.gif" BORDER=0> at: 6/5/02 8:00:05 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/ufrogggystyle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Frogggystyle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardaholic</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/02 11:45:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2562.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/frogggystyle/eqpics/bellohead.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Medical Profession today..</span><hr size=1> I flat out refuse to believe that the &quot;vast majority&quot; of doctors are apathetic and incompetent, even if they are in the south. That is the most disturbing thing I have ever heard. I would be more open to believing the U.S. is a communist country than to believe what you are suggesting. Perhaps your fiance was just a complete pain in the ass to every doctor he saw. Maybe your story is only being told from one side. I have worked in MANY medical settings in the last 10 years. NEVER, not ONCE have I EVER met an apathetic or incompetent doctor. It is very disturbing to hear someone even hint at such an absurd idea. Sure, you may have run into one, maybe two...or however many you claim, but I have never worked with anyone that didn't care about their patients and try to do everything to make them better.<br><br>Go become a medical professional and do it for many years, then come tell me that the vast majority of doctors and other health care professional are apathetic to patients. You can't do it, even if you wanted to. Most everyone I have ever worked with really do care about every patient they have had. The only patients health care providers don't like dealing with are the pains in the ass that think they know more than the doctors and treat the health care providers like second class citizens like they don't know their head from their ass. Even still, doctors and health care providers STILL go out of their way to try and treat that patient, even though people like that deserve no kindness from anybody.<br><br>Doctors do not just &quot;toss aside&quot; all previous records and information. Every written document on from patient's medical history is needed to track progress or change in a situation. The &quot;re-doing of the expensive scans and tests&quot; are necessary to evaluate the patient's CURRENT condition. If a doctor was relying on a patient's history from 3 years prior with no current information to go by (even if it is only 2 weeks old) then they may as well be starting from scratch. Scans and tests are expensive, yes. If it is a money issue, then I advise ya to move to Canada and become a citizen to enjoy their socialized health care system. <br><br>Managed care is not always a good way to go, yet some people can only afford that type of health care; where they don't have a choice in who they see. The choice in your coverage is ultimately yours to make, just as it is your choice to choose where you work and where you live. Get different medical coverage if managed care is not working for you. Yeah, it'll cost ya...but what is more important in the long run, your fiance's current/future health...or your current pocket book's balance?<br><br>Doctors normally have a set &quot;script&quot; of things to do when they see a patient. If a patient exhibits (A) symptoms then they are treated with the typical (A) treatment. If a doctor senses that the patient is not following explicit directions, they may start the person all over on the exact same treatment until they can be certain that the patient is indeed trying to follow directions. You wouldn't believe how many people will leave a medical center with medications and explicit directions to do/not do a certain activity and then not even take their meds and totally disregard the doctor's advice. And then they come back saying, &quot;It is the doctor's fault that I am not better because they didn't treat me right!&quot; You can lead a horse to water...<br><br>And, sure, you have a few incompetent health care providers out there...somewhere. And if you have run into that handful then you have my sympathy. But that is what medical boards are for...that is why we have residencies....that is why it takes, typically, 8 years of college education to become a doctor and then another 2-4 years in residency focusing on one area outside of general family practice. Even so, after 10-12 years of formal education and hands on training, doctors do not know everything and there are things they can/will miss. (Read: Humans are not perfect.) The only thing you can do is write out a complete history of the issue and submit it to the medical facility you visited (or hire an attorney), then go find another provider with better credentials. But to label every doctor (regardless if it is the south) as apathetic and incompetent is reckless and slanderous. <br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/uuhgreebugga.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Uhgre